The patient is experiencing symptoms of circumoral numbness, paresthesias in the fingertips, and anxiety shortly after a total thyroidectomy. These symptoms are classic signs of hypocalcemia, which can occur after thyroid surgery due to damage or removal of the parathyroid glands. Hypocalcemia can lead to neuromuscular irritability, manifesting as paresthesias and anxiety. The Chvostek sign, which is a twitch of the facial muscles in response to tapping over the facial nerve, is a clinical sign of hypocalcemia.

The answer is (B)
